What is the cause of a transient ischaemic attack?'
Transient ischaemic attacks (TIAs) are often referred to as'mini-strokes'. Their exact cause is uncertain, but they are thought to be caused by a temporary reduction in blood flow to the brain, which deprives the brain cells of oxygen and nutrients. This reduction in blood supply may be due to
A thrombus (blood clot) blocking a blood vessel in the brain or neck;
A blood clot embolus from another part of the body, such as the heart;
A narrowing of the arteries due to atherosclerosis (plaque build-up);
A cerebral tumour;
A blood vessel anomaly, such as an aneurysm or arteriovenous malformation (AVM).
